definition.value: A `pitchfork bifurcation` [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000122] in which two symmetrical stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133] fixed points [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000086] and an unstable [not TEDDY_0000133] fixed point [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000086] appear from a stable fixed point.

A spiral point [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000091] which is stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two negative complex conjugate eigenvalues. The fixed point is surrounded by behaviours [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] spiralling downward the fixed point, corresponding to decaying oscillations.

A spiral point [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000091] which is unstable [not TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two positive complex conjugate eigenvalues. The fixed point is surrounded by behaviours [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] spiralling upward the fixed point, corresponding to growing oscillations.

If all trajectories [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] that start near the limit cycle [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000051] (both inside and outside) spiral outward, then the limit cycle is called unstable.
A fixed point [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000086] which is not Liapunov stable [not TEDDY_0000113].
An inflection point is a point on a curve at which the sign of the curvature (i.e., the concavity) changes. Inflection points may be stationary points, but are not local maxima or local minima.
A magnitude of an oscillation.

Behaviour diversification describes the way one or several temporal behaviours [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] are modified or related upon interaction with information external to the system considered.

A solution x*(t) of the n-dimentional system x ̇=X(x, t) is Liapunov stable, if no matter how small is the permitted deviation, measured by epsilon, there still exists a nonzero tolerance, measured by delta, in the initial conditions when the system is activated, allowing it to run satisfactorily.
An invariant set is called half-stable if there exist a stable and an unstable manifold with respect to the invariant set.

An asymptotically stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000097] behaviour [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] to which only behaviours starting in a restricted neighbourhood will converge.

An asymptotically stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000097] behaviour [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] to which all other behaviours will converge independent of the initial distance.
A fixed point node [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000087] which is stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two negative eigenvalues.
A fixed point node [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000087] which is unstable [not TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two positive eigenvalues.

A star [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000090] which is stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two identical negative eigenvalues. All other trajectories [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] of the system are straight lines towards the fixed point.

A star [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000090] which is unstable [not TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two identical positive eigenvalues. All other trajectories [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] of the system are straight lines away the fixed point.

A degenerated node [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000093] which is stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two identical negative eigenvalues.
A degenerated node [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000093] which is unstable [not TEDDY_0000133], i.e. for which the Jacobian matrix has two identical positive eigenvalues.
A 'temporal behaviour' [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] which never repeats its state.
A characteristic describing the order of the successive states of a curve.

If trajectories [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] on one side of the limit cycle [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000051] spiral inward and on the other side spiral outward, it is called semistable.
A `temporal behaviour` [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] which converges to some `limit behaviour` [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000085].

A bifurcation [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000053] in which at least two limit cycles [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000051] or fixed points TEDDY_0000086 are involved. It can not be detected within a small neighborhood of a fixed point.
A characteristic describing stability of a 'temporal behaviour' [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083], i.e. how far from each other solutions with close initial states become as time passes.

The solution x*(t), t >= t0 is Poincaré stable, if all sufficiently small disturbances of the initial value a* lead to half-paths remaining for all later time at a small distance from the half-path H* with initial point a*.

A Liapunov stable [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000133] solution [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] is uniformly stable if its sensitivity to disturbance does not increase indefinitely with time.
A heteroclinic orbit is a trajectory [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] of a dynamical system that tends to two different invariant sets as time approaches positive and negative infinities.
A homoclinic orbit is a trajectory [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] of a dynamical system that tends to the same invariant set as time approaches positive and negative infinities.

A global bifurcation [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000147] in which two saddles [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000089] are only connected at the bifurcation point by a heteroclinic saddle connection [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000101]. This saddle connection does not exist below and above the bifurcation.

A global bifurcation [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000147] in which a homoclinic saddle connection [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000100] only exists at the bifurcation point. There exists a Limit Cycle [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000051] either below or above the bifurcation.

A fixed point [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000086] is said to be hyperbolic if all eigenvalues of the Jacobian matrix have non-zero real parts. A limit cycle [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000051] is called hyperbolic if the fixed point of the Poincare ́map is hyperbolic.
A network motif in which two transcription factors regulate each other with the regulation signs of the two interactions leading to a positive feedback loop.
A positive feedback loop made of two positive interactions, so that the two transcription factors activate each other.
A positive feedback loop made of two negative interactions, so that the two transcription factors repress each other.
A simple topological generalization of the 'three-node feed-forward loop' [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000037] based on multiplication of the output node.
A two-node double-negative loop.

A system x ̇=f(x), x ∈ Rn (1), defined in a region D ⊂ Rn is called structurally stable in a region D0 ⊂ D if for any sufficiently C1-close in D system x ̇=g(x), x ∈ Rn (2), there are regions U, V ⊂ D, D0 ⊂ U such that (1) is topologically equivalent in U to (2) in V.

The attractor [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000094] is regular or simple if the phase trajectories [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000083] on the attractor are stable according both to Lyapunov [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000113] and to Poisson [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000149].
A 'bifurcation of limit cycle' [http://identifiers.org/teddy/TEDDY_0000070] in which a limit cycle collides with a non-hyperbolic cycle.
A quantitative characteristic of the graph of a function.
According to the intuitive definition of excitability, small perturbations near the equilibrium can cause large excursions for the solution before it returns to the equilibrium.
A type of computational resource used in bioinformatics.
A bioinformatics package or tool, e.g. a standalone application or web service.
A digital data archive typically based around a relational model but sometimes using an object-oriented, tree or graph-based model.
An ontology of biological or bioinformatics concepts and relations, a controlled vocabulary, structured glossary etc.
A directory on disk from which files are read.
Controlled vocabulary from National Library of Medicine. The MeSH thesaurus is used to index articles in biomedical journals for the Medline/PubMED databases.
Controlled vocabulary for gene names (symbols) from HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee.
Compendium of controlled vocabularies for the biomedical domain (Unified Medical Language System).
